04844nam a22006135i 9780804773775DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20202010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047737757 a10.1515/97808047737752doi  a(DE-B1597)564032  a(OCoLC)1224278107  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBF611.T69 2010 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a302.100aToward an Anthropology of the Will /cC. Jason Throop, Keith M. Murphy. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- t1. Willing Contours: Locating Volition in Anthropological Theory -- t2. In the Midst of Action -- t3. Moral Willing As Narrative Re-Envisioning -- t4. By the Will of Others or by One's Own Action? -- t5. Willful Souls: Dreaming and the Dialectics of Self-Experience Among the Tzotzil Maya of Highland Chiapas, Mexico -- t6. Transforming Will/Transforming Culture -- t7. How Can Will Be Expressed and What Role Does the Imagination Play? -- t8. Emil Kraepelin on Pathologies of the Will -- tAfterword: Willing in Context -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToward an Anthropology of the Will is the first book that systematically explores volition from an ethnographically informed anthropological point of view. While philosophers have for centuries puzzled over the degree to which individuals are "free" to choose how to act in the world, anthropologists have either assumed that the will is a stable, constant fact of the human condition or simply ignored it. Although they are usually quite comfortable discussing the relationship between culture and cognition or culture and emotion, anthropologists have not yet focused on how culture and volition are interconnected. The contributors to this book draw upon their unique insights and research experience to address fundamental questions, including: What forms does the will take in culture? How is willing experienced? How does it relate to emotion and cognition? What does imagination have to do with willing? What is the connection between morality, virtue, and willing? Exploring such questions, the book moves beyond old debates about "freedom" and "determinacy" to demonstrate how a richly nuanced anthropological approach to the cultural experience of willing can help shape theories of social action in the human sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aStrathern, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGood, Byron J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThroop, C. Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMattingly, Cheryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHollan, Douglas W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMageo, Jeannette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Keith M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroark, Kevin P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarro, Linda C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Keith M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStewart, Pamela J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThroop, C. Jason, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804773775zCo-ac